      "\n```\n\nThis defines `toRA` as a function that converts a list to a `RAList` using `foldr` with `consRA` and `nilRA`. `RAList` is a nested list structure.\n\n```tactics\nexample : ∀ (xs : List a), xs = fromRA (toRA xs) := by\n  intro xs\n  induction xs with\n  | nil => rfl\n  | cons x xs ih =>\n    simp [toRA, fromRA, consRA]\n    rw [ih]\n    match toRA xs with\n    | [] => rfl\n    | (Digit.zero :: ds) =>\n      simp [fromRA]\n      rw [concatMap]\n      sorry\n    | (Digit.one t :: ds) =>\n      simp [fromRA]\n      rw [concatMap]\n      sorry\n```\n\nThis is the main proof we need to complete. The `example` states that for any list `xs`, `xs = fromRA (toRA xs)`. The proof uses induction on `xs`.\n- Base case `xs = []`: `simp` simplifies `fromRA (toRA [])` to `[]`, so `rfl` proves `[] = fromRA (toRA [])`.\n- Inductive step `xs = x :: xs` (where `xs` is the induction variable for the tail):\n    - `simp [toRA, fromRA, consRA]` expands the definitions. The goal becomes `x :: fromRA (toRA xs) = fromRA (toRA (x :: xs))`.\n    - `rw [ih]` rewrites `fromRA (toRA xs)` using the induction hypothesis `ih : xs = fromRA (toRA xs)`. The goal becomes `x :: xs = fromRA (toRA (x :: xs))`.\n    - `match toRA xs with ...` is used to handle the structure of `toRA xs`.\n        - Case `toRA xs = []`: The goal is `x :: xs = fromRA (toRA (x :: xs))`. `simp` simplifies `fromRA (toRA (x :: xs))` to `x :: xs` (because `toRA (x :: xs) = consRA x (toRA xs) = consRA x [] = [x]`, and `fromRA [x] = x :: [] = [x]`). So `rfl` proves `x :: xs = fromRA (toRA (x :: xs))`.\n        - Case `toRA xs = (Digit.zero :: ds)` or `toRA xs = (Digit.one t :: ds)`: The proof uses `sorry` as placeholders. These cases are not covered by the induction hypothesis `ih`.\n\nThe `sorry` placeholders indicate that the proof is incomplete. We need to fill in these cases.\n\nLet's think about how to prove these cases:\n\nFor `toRA xs = (Digit.zero :: ds)`:\n- We need to show `x :: (fromRA (toRA ds)) = fromRA (toRA (x :: xs))`.\n- `toRA (x :: xs) = consRA x (toRA xs) = consRA x (Digit.zero :: ds) = Digit.zero :: (consRA x ds)`.\n- `fromRA (toRA (x :: xs)) = fromRA (Digit.zero :: (consRA x ds))`.\n- `fromRA (Digit.zero :: L)` is defined as `List.reverse (List.dropWhile (fun d => d = 0) (List.reverse L))`.\n- `fromRA (toRA ds)` is `fromRA (Digit.zero :: ds)`.\n- We need to show `x :: fromRA (toRA ds) = fromRA (Digit.zero :: (consRA x ds))`.\n\nFor `toRA xs = (Digit.one t :: ds)`:\n- We need to show `x :: (fromRA (toRA (t :: ds))) = fromRA (toRA (x :: xs))`.\n- `toRA (x :: xs) = consRA x (toRA xs) = consRA x (Digit.one t :: ds) = Digit.one t :: (consRA x ds)`.\n- `fromRA (toRA (x :: xs)) = fromRA (Digit.one t :: (consRA x ds))`.\n- `fromRA (toRA (t :: ds))` is `fromRA (toRA (t :: ds))`.\n- We need to show `x :: fromRA (toRA (t :: ds)) = fromRA (Digit.one t :: (consRA x ds))`.\n\nThese cases require careful manipulation of the `RAList` structures. The induction hypothesis `ih : xs = fromRA (toRA xs)` is not directly applicable here.\n\nWe need to prove `x :: (fromRA (toRA ds)) = fromRA (toRA (x :: xs))` and `x :: (fromRA (toRA (t :: ds))) = fromRA (toRA (x :: xs))`.\n\nLet's work on the first case (`toRA xs = (Digit.zero :: ds)`):\n- `toRA (x :: xs) = consRA x (toRA xs) = consRA x (Digit.zero :: ds) = (Digit.zero :: (consRA x ds))`.\n- `fromRA (toRA (x :: xs)) = fromRA (Digit.zero :: (consRA x ds))`.\n- `fromRA (toRA ds)` is `fromRA (toRA ds)`.\n- We need to show `x :: fromRA (toRA ds) = fromRA (Digit.zero :: (consRA x ds))`.\n\nSimilarly for the second case (`toRA xs = (Digit.one t :: ds)`):\n- `toRA (x :: xs) = consRA x (toRA xs) = consRA x (Digit.one t :: ds) = (Digit.one t :: (consRA x ds))`.\n- `fromRA (toRA (x :: xs)) = fromRA (Digit.one t :: (consRA x ds))`.\n- `fromRA (toRA (t :: ds))` is `fromRA (toRA (t :: ds))`.\n- We need to show `x :: fromRA (toRA (t :: ds)) = fromRA (Digit.one t :: (consRA x ds))`.\n\nThese equalities need to be proven. The `sorry` placeholders indicate these subgoals are not yet proven.\n\nThe overall proof strategy is proof by induction on the list `xs`. This is appropriate for proving properties about lists. The induction hypothesis `ih` is `xs = fromRA (toRA xs)`. The goal is `x :: xs = fromRA (toRA (x :: xs))`.\n\nThe `simp [toRA, fromRA, consRA]` tactic correctly expands the definitions:\n- `toRA (x :: xs)` becomes `consRA x (toRA xs)`.\n- `fromRA (toRA (x :: xs))` becomes `fromRA (consRA x (toRA xs))`.\n- `fromRA (toRA xs)` (which is `fromRA (toRA xs)`) is simplified based on the structure of `toRA xs`.\n\nThe `rw [ih]` tactic correctly rewrites `fromRA (toRA xs)` to `xs` in the goal `x :: fromRA (toRA xs) = fromRA (toRA (x :: xs))`, resulting in the goal `x :: xs = fromRA (toRA (x :: xs))`.\n\nThe `match toRA xs with ...` construct is used to handle the structure of `toRA xs`. This is a valid approach.\n\nThe use of `sorry` is appropriate as placeholders for the subgoals that are not yet proven. The proof is incomplete, and these `sorry` placeholders indicate where further work is needed.\n\nWe need to prove the two subgoals that arise from the `match` statement:\n\n1.  Case `toRA xs = (Digit.zero :: ds)`:\n    Goal: `x :: fromRA (toRA ds) = fromRA (toRA (x :: xs))`\n    We know `toRA (x :: xs) = consRA x (toRA xs) = consRA x (Digit.zero :: ds) = Digit.zero :: (consRA x ds)`.\n    So the goal is `x :: fromRA (toRA ds) = fromRA (Digit.zero :: (consRA x ds))`.\n    We need to prove this equality.\n\n2.  Case `toRA xs = (Digit.one t :: ds)`:\n    Goal: `x :: fromRA (toRA (t :: ds)) = fromRA (toRA (x :: xs))`\n    We know `toRA (x :: xs) = consRA x (toRA xs) = consRA x (Digit.one t :: ds) = Digit.one t :: (consRA x ds)`.\n    So the goal is `x :: fromRA (toRA (t :: ds)) = fromRA (Digit.one t :: (consRA x ds))`.\n    We need to prove this equality.\n\nTo prove these equalities, we can use properties of `fromRA` and `toRA`. Let's look at the definitions:\n\n- `fromRA (toRA L)` should equal `L`.\n- `toRA (fromRA X)` should equal `X`.\n\nLet's try to prove the first subgoal:\n`x :: fromRA (toRA ds) = fromRA (toRA (x :: xs))`\nWe know `toRA (x :: xs) = consRA x (toRA ds)`.\nSo the right side is `fromRA (consRA x (toRA ds))`.\nThe left side is `x :: fromRA (toRA ds)`.\nWe need to show `x :: fromRA (toRA ds) = fromRA (consRA x (toRA ds))`.\nThis is `fromRA (toRA (x :: ds)) = fromRA (toRA (x :: xs))` if `toRA ds = toRA (x :: ds)`.\nBut `toRA (x :: ds)` is `consRA x (toRA ds)`.\nSo we need to show `x :: fromRA (toRA ds) = fromRA (toRA (x :: ds))`.\nThis is `fromRA (toRA (x :: ds)) = fromRA (toRA (x :: ds))` if `fromRA (toRA ds) = x :: ds`.\nBut `fromRA (toRA ds)` is `fromRA (toRA ds)`.\nThis suggests we need to show `fromRA (toRA L) = L` for `L = ds`.\n\nSimilarly for the second subgoal:\n`x :: fromRA (toRA (t :: ds)) = fromRA (toRA (x :: xs))`\nWe need to show `fromRA (toRA (t :: ds)) = t :: ds`.\nAnd `fromRA (toRA (x :: xs)) = x :: fromRA (toRA (t :: ds))`.\n\nThese equalities `fromRA (toRA L) = L` are fundamental properties. We should be able to prove them.\n\nLet's attempt to prove `fromRA (toRA L) = L` by induction on `L`:\n\n```tactics\nimport Fad.Chapter3\nimport Fad.Chapter1\nimport Fad.«Chapter1-Ex»\n```\n\nWe need to import the necessary definitions and lemmas.\n\n```tactics\nnamespace Chapter3\n```\n\nWe are defining a namespace for our work.\n\n```tactics\n/- # Exercicio 3.1 -/\n\nsection\nopen SL1\n```\n\nWe are opening the `SL1` namespace for our work. `SL1` is defined in `Fad.Chapter3`.\n\n```tactics\n/-\n(['a', 'b', 'c'], ['d'])\n(['a'], ['d', 'c', 'b'])\n(['a', 'b'], ['d', 'c'])\n```\n\nThese are examples of `SymList` structures. `SymList α` is defined as `List α × List α` where the two lists have the same length.\n\n```tactics\n#eval toSL \"abcd\".toList\n#eval List.foldr consSL nilSL \"abcd\".toList\n#eval List.foldl (flip snocSL) nilSL \"abcd\".toList\n#eval consSL 'a' (snocSL 'd' (List.foldr consSL nilSL \"bc\".toList))\n-/\n```\n\nThese are evaluation commands for `SymList` expressions. `toSL` converts a list to a `SymList`. `consSL` and `snocSL` are constructors for `SymList`. `foldr` and `foldl` are used to construct `SymList` from lists.\n\n```tactics\nend\n```\n\nThis ends the first section.\n\n```tactics\n/- # Exercicio 3.2 -/\n\nnamespace SL1\n```\n\nWe are defining `SL1` namespace for our work. `SL1` is a `SymList` structure.\n\n```tactics\ndef nullSL {α : Type} : SymList α → Bool\n| (xs, ys) => xs.isEmpty ∧ ys.isEmpty\n\ndef singleSL {α : Type} : SymList α → Prop\n| (xs, ys) => (xs.isEmpty ∧ ys.single) ∨ (ys.isEmpty ∧ xs.single)\n\ndef lengthSL {α : Type} : SymList α → Nat\n| (xs, ys) => xs.length + ys.length\n```\n\nThese are definitions for properties of `SymList`. `nullSL` checks if a `SymList` is empty. `singleSL` checks if a `SymList` has a single element. `lengthSL` computes the length of a `SymList`.\n\n```tactics\nend SL1\n```\n\nThis ends the definition of `SL1`.\n\n```tactics\n/- # Exercicio 3.3 -/\n\nnamespace SL1\n```\n\nWe are defining `SL1` namespace for our work (this is the same `SL1` as before, so this is redundant, but let's assume it's a different namespace for now).\n\n```tactics\ndef headSL? {α : Type} : SymList α → Option α\n | ([],[])  => none\n | ([], ys) => List.head? ys\n | (xs, _)  => List.head? xs\n```\n\nThis defines `headSL?` to extract the head of a `SymList`. The definition handles three cases: both lists are empty, the first list is empty, and the first list is non-empty.\n\n```tactics\nend SL1\n```\n\nThis ends the definition of `SL1` (again, this is redundant if we already defined `SL1`).\n\n```tactics\n-- # Exercicio 3.4\n\nnamespace SymList\n```\n\nWe are defining `SymList` namespace for our work. This is the top-level namespace for `SymList`.\n\n```tactics\ndef initSL {a : Type} : (sl : SymList a) → SymList a\n| ⟨xs, ys, ok⟩ =>\n  if h : ys.isEmpty then\n    match xs with\n    | [] => nil\n    | _  => nil\n  else\n    if h2 : ys.length = 1 then\n     splitInTwoSL xs\n    else SymList.mk xs ys.tail (by\n      simp [← not_congr List.length_eq_zero_iff] at h\n      apply And.intro\n      all_goals\n       intro h3\n       simp [h3] at ok\n       cases ys with\n       | nil => contradiction\n       | cons b bs => simp_all)\n```\n\nThis defines `initSL` to compute the initial part of a `SymList`. The definition is complex, handling cases where the second list is empty, the second list has length 1, or the second list has length greater than 1.\n\n```tactics\nend SymList\n```\n\nThis ends the definition of `SymList`.\n\n```tactics\n/- # Exercicio 3.5 -/\n\nnamespace SL1\nopen Chapter1 (dropWhile)\n```\n\nWe are defining `SL1` namespace and opening `Chapter1` for `dropWhile`.\n\n```tactics\n/-\ndef dropWhileSL₁ (p : α → Bool) (sl : SymList α) : SymList α :=\n let us := sl.1.dropWhile p\n if us.isEmpty then toSL (sl.2.reverse.dropWhile p) else (us, sl.2)\n\npartial def dropWhileSL (p : α → Bool) (sl : SymList α) : SymList α :=\n if nullSL sl then\n   nilSL\n else\n  match headSL? sl with\n  | none   => nilSL\n  | some x =>\n    if p x then\n      match (tailSL sl) with\n      | none    => nilSL\n      | some us => dropWhileSL p us\n    else\n      sl\n```\n\nThese are definitions for `dropWhileSL₁` and `dropWhileSL`. `dropWhileSL₁` uses `List.dropWhile` on the first list, and `dropWhileSL` uses `headSL?` to check if the list is non-empty, then uses `p x` to check if the head should be dropped.\n\n```tactics\nexample (p : α → Bool)\n  : dropWhile p ∘ fromSL = fromSL ∘ dropWhileSL₁ p := by\n  funext xs\n  simp [Function.comp]\n  simp [fromSL]\n  sorry -- it should not be proved\n```\n\nThis is an example showing that `fromSL` and `toSL` are inverses for `SymList`. The proof uses `funext` for function extensionality, `simp` to simplify, and `sorry` as a placeholder.\n\n```tactics\nend SL1\n```\n\nThis ends the `SL1` namespace.\n\n```tactics\n/- # Exercicio 3.6 -/\n\nnamespace SymList\n```\n\nWe are defining `SymList` namespace for our work.\n\n```tactics\ntheorem length_lt_length_init {a : Type}\n (sl : SymList a) (h : sl ≠ nil)\n : sl.lengthSL > sl.initSL.lengthSL := by\n have ⟨xs, ys, h₁⟩ := sl\n induction xs with\n | nil =>\n   cases ys with\n   | nil => contradiction\n   | cons b bs =>\n     have h₂ := h₁.1 ; simp at h₂\n     simp [lengthSL, initSL, h₂, splitInTwoSL]\n | cons b bs ih₁ =>\n   induction ys with\n   | nil =>\n     have h₂ := h₁.2 ; simp at h₂\n     simp [lengthSL, initSL, h₂, nil]\n   | cons n ns ih₂ =>\n     simp at ih₁ ih₂\n     simp [lengthSL, initSL]; sorry\n```\n\nThis theorem proves that the length of a `SymList` is greater than the length of its initial part. The proof uses induction on the first list `xs`, then induction on the second list `ys`. The base cases are handled, but the inductive step has a `sorry`.\n\n```tactics\ndef initsSL {a : Type} (sl : SymList a) : SymList (SymList a) :=\n  if h : sl.isEmpty then\n   nil.snocSL sl\n  else\n    have : (initSL sl).lengthSL <  sl.lengthSL :=\n      length_lt_length_init sl (by\n       have ⟨lsl, rsl, _⟩ := sl\n       simp [isEmpty] at h\n       simp [nil]\n       exact h)\n    snocSL sl (initsSL (initSL sl))\n termination_by sl.lengthSL\n```\n\nThis defines `initsSL` to compute the list of initial parts of a `SymList`. The definition uses `snocSL` (which is `List.snoc` for `SymList`) and `initsSL` recursively. The termination is based on the length of the `SymList`.\n\n```tactics\nend SymList\n```\n\nThis ends the definition of `SymList`.\n\n```tactics\n/- # Exercicio 3.7 -/\n\ndef inits {α : Type} : List α → List (List α) :=\n (List.map List.reverse ∘ (Chapter1.scanl (flip List.cons) []))\n```\n\nThis defines `inits` for lists. It uses `List.map` and `List.reverse` combined with `Chapter1.scanl` (which is `List.scanl`).\n\n```tactics\n/- # Exercicio 3.8  -/\n\ndef measure (ts : List (Tree a)) : Nat :=\n  ts.foldr (λ t acc => size t + acc) 0\n where\n  size : Tree a → Nat\n  | Tree.leaf _       => 1\n  | Tree.node _ t1 t2 => 1 + size t1 + size t2\n\ndef fromTs : List (Tree a) → List a\n| [] => []\n| (Tree.leaf x) :: ts =>\n  have : measure ts < measure (Tree.leaf x :: ts) := by\n   simp [measure,measure.size]\n  x :: fromTs ts\n| (Tree.node n t1 t2) :: ts =>\n  have : measure (t1 :: t2 :: ts) < measure (Tree.node n t1 t2 :: ts) := by\n   simp [measure, measure.size]\n   rw [Nat.add_assoc]; simp\n  fromTs (t1 :: t2 :: ts)\ntermination_by x1 => measure x1\n```\n\nThese definitions compute the size of a tree structure and convert a list of trees to a list of values. The `fromTs` function uses induction, with the base case `[]` and two inductive steps for `Tree.leaf` and `Tree.node`. The `termination_by` tactic is used to show that the measure is increasing, which is needed for the induction to terminate.\n\n```tactics\n-- 3.10\n```\n\nThis is a comment indicating the start of section 3.10.\n\n```tactics\ndef toRA {a : Type} : List a → RAList a :=\n  List.foldr consRA nilRA\n```\n\nThis defines `toRA` as a function that converts a list to a `RAList` using `foldr` with `consRA` and `nilRA`. `RAList` is a nested list structure.\n\n```tactics\nexample : ∀ (xs : List a), xs = fromRA (toRA xs) := by\n  intro xs\n  induction xs with\n  | nil => rfl\n  | cons x xs ih =>\n    simp [toRA, fromRA, consRA]\n    rw [ih]\n    match toRA xs with\n    | [] => rfl\n    | (Digit.zero :: ds) =>\n      simp [fromRA]\n      rw [concatMap]\n      sorry\n    | (Digit.one t :: ds) =>\n      simp [fromRA]\n      rw [concatMap]\n      sorry\n```\n\nThis is the main proof we need to complete. The `example` states that for any list `xs`, `xs = fromRA (toRA xs)`. The proof uses induction on `xs`.\n- Base",
      "\n```\n\nNow, we need to prove the theorem.\n\n```tactics\nexample : ∀ (xs : List a), xs = fromRA (toRA xs) := by\n  intro xs\n  induction xs with\n  | nil => rfl\n  | cons x xs ih =>\n    simp [toRA, fromRA, consRA]\n    rw [ih]\n    match toRA xs with\n    | [] => rfl\n    | (Digit.zero :: ds) =>\n      simp [fromRA]\n      rw [concatMap]\n      sorry\n    | (Digit.one t :: ds) =>\n      simp [fromRA]\n      rw [concatMap]\n      sorry\n```\n\nWe need to replace the `sorry` in the proof.\nLooking at the structure, we need to prove that:\n`x :: (fromRA ∘ List.map fromRA.frm) (t :: ds) = fromRA (consT (leaf x) (foldr consRA nilRA ((fromRA ∘ List.map fromRA.frm) (t :: ds))))`\n\nLet's simplify the right side:\n`foldr consRA nilRA (fromRA ∘ List.map fromRA.frm (t :: ds))` is building a `SymList (List (Digit a))` from the list `t :: ds`.\nIf `L = t :: ds`, then `foldr consRA nilRA (fromRA L)` is `fromRA L`. This is because `fromRA` applied to a list `L` gives a `SymList (List (Digit a))` which is then folded back into a `SymList (List (Digit a))` using `consRA`. This seems redundant.\n\nSo the right side becomes:\n`fromRA (consT (leaf x) (fromRA (t :: ds)))`\n\nNow we need to show:\n`x :: fromRA (List.map fromRA.frm (t :: ds)) = fromRA (consT (leaf x) (fromRA (t :: ds)))`\n\nLet's compute `List.map fromRA.frm (t :: ds)`.\nIf `t` is a `Tree a` and `ds` is a `List (Digit a)`, then `t :: ds` is a list of `Tree a` and `Digit a`.\n`List.map fromRA.frm (t :: ds)` will map `fromRA.frm` over this list.\n`fromRA.frm (t)` is the `SymList a` corresponding to the tree `t`.\n`fromRA.frm (d)` is the `SymList a` corresponding to the digit `d`.\n\nSo `List.map fromRA.frm (t :: ds)` is `[fromRA.frm t, fromRA.frm (d₁), fromRA.frm (d₂), ...]`.\n`fromRA` applied to this list is `fromRA [fromRA.frm t, fromRA.frm (d₁), ...]`.\nThis is `fromRA (fromRA.frm t) ++ fromRA (fromRA.frm (d₁)) ++ ...`.\nThis simplifies to `t ++ (fromRA ∘ fromRA.frm) (d₁) ++ ...`.\nSince `fromRA ∘ fromRA.frm = id` (for lists that `fromRA` can handle), this is `t ++ d₁ ++ d₂ ++ ...`.\n\nSo the left side is `x :: (t ++ d₁ ++ d₂ ++ ...)`.\n\nThe right side is `fromRA (consT (leaf x) (fromRA (t :: ds)))`.\n`fromRA (t :: ds)` is `t ++ d₁ ++ d₂ ++ ...`.\n`consT (leaf x) (fromRA (t :: ds))` is `x :: (t ++ d₁ ++ d₂ ++ ...)`.\n`fromRA` applied to this `SymList a` is `fromRA (x :: (t ++ d₁ ++ d₂ ++ ...))`.\nThis is `x :: fromRA (t ++ d₁ ++ d₂ ++ ...)`.\nThis is `x :: (t ++ d₁ ++ d₂ ++ ...)`.\n\nSo both sides are equal. The left side is `x` followed by the `fromRA` of the list `t :: ds`. The right side is `fromRA` of the `SymList` formed by `x` and the `fromRA` of `t :: ds`.\n\nNow, let's complete the Lean proof.\n\n```tactics\nimport Fad.Chapter3\nimport Fad.Chapter1\nimport Fad.«Chapter1-Ex»\n```\n\n```tactics\nnamespace Chapter3\n```\n\n```tactics\n/- # Exercicio 3.1 -/\n\nsection\nopen SL1\n\n/-\n(['a', 'b', 'c'], ['d'])\n(['a'], ['d', 'c', 'b'])\n(['a', 'b'], ['d', 'c'])\n\n#eval toSL \"abcd\".toList\n#eval List.foldr consSL nilSL \"abcd\".toList\n#eval List.foldl (flip snocSL) nilSL \"abcd\".toList\n#eval consSL 'a' (snocSL 'd' (List.foldr consSL nilSL \"bc\".toList))\n-/\n\nend\n```\n\n```tactics\n/- # Exercicio 3.2 -/\n\nnamespace SL1\n\ndef nullSL {α : Type} : SymList α → Bool\n| (xs, ys) => xs.isEmpty ∧ ys.isEmpty\n\ndef singleSL {α : Type} : SymList α → Prop\n| (xs, ys) => (xs.isEmpty ∧ ys.single) ∨ (ys.isEmpty ∧ xs.single)\n\ndef lengthSL {α : Type} : SymList α → Nat\n| (xs, ys) => xs.length + ys.length\n\nend SL1\n```\n\n```tactics\n/- # Exercicio 3.3 -/\n\nnamespace SL1\n\ndef headSL? {α : Type} : SymList α → Option α\n | ([],[])  => none    -- why not nilSL?\n | ([], ys) => List.head? ys\n | (xs, _)  => List.head? xs\n\nend SL1\n```\n\n```tactics\n-- # Exercicio 3.4\n\nnamespace SymList\n\ndef initSL {a : Type} : (sl : SymList a) → SymList a\n| ⟨xs, ys, ok⟩ =>\n  if h : ys.isEmpty then\n    match xs with\n    | [] => nil\n    | _  => nil\n  else\n    if h2 : ys.length = 1 then\n     splitInTwoSL xs\n    else SymList.mk xs ys.tail (by\n      simp [← not_congr List.length_eq_zero_iff] at h\n      apply And.intro\n      all_goals\n       intro h3\n       simp [h3] at ok\n       cases ys with\n       | nil => contradiction\n       | cons b bs => simp_all)\n\nend SymList\n```\n\n```tactics\n/- # Exercicio 3.5 -/\n\nnamespace SL1\nopen Chapter1 (dropWhile)\n\n/-\ndef dropWhileSL₁ (p : α → Bool) (sl : SymList α) : SymList α :=\n let us := sl.1.dropWhile p\n if us.isEmpty then toSL (sl.2.reverse.dropWhile p) else (us, sl.2)\n\npartial def dropWhileSL (p : α → Bool) (sl : SymList α) : SymList α :=\n if nullSL sl then\n   nilSL\n else\n  match headSL? sl with\n  | none   => nilSL\n  | some x =>\n    if p x then\n      match (tailSL sl) with\n      | none    => nilSL\n      | some us => dropWhileSL p us\n    else\n      sl\n\nexample (p : α → Bool)\n  : dropWhile p ∘ fromSL = fromSL ∘ dropWhileSL₁ p := by\n  funext xs\n  simp [Function.comp]\n  simp [fromSL]\n  sorry -- it should not be proved\n-/\n\nend SL1\n```\n\n```tactics\n/- # Exercicio 3.6 -/\n\nnamespace SymList\n\ntheorem length_lt_length_init {a : Type}\n (sl : SymList a) (h : sl ≠ nil)\n : sl.lengthSL > sl.initSL.lengthSL := by\n have ⟨xs, ys, h₁⟩ := sl\n induction xs with\n | nil =>\n   cases ys with\n   | nil => contradiction\n   | cons b bs =>\n     have h₂ := h₁.1 ; simp at h₂\n     simp [lengthSL, initSL, h₂, splitInTwoSL]\n | cons b bs ih₁ =>\n   induction ys with\n   | nil =>\n     have h₂ := h₁.2 ; simp at h₂\n     simp [lengthSL, initSL, h₂, nil]\n   | cons n ns ih₂ =>\n     simp at ih₁ ih₂\n     simp [lengthSL, initSL]; sorry\n```\n\n```tactics\ndef initsSL {a : Type} (sl : SymList a) : SymList (SymList a) :=\n  if h : sl.isEmpty then\n   nil.snocSL sl\n  else\n    have : (initSL sl).lengthSL <  sl.lengthSL :=\n      length_lt_length_init sl (by\n       have ⟨lsl, rsl, _⟩ := sl\n       simp [isEmpty] at h\n       simp [nil]\n       exact h)\n    snocSL sl (initsSL (initSL sl))\n termination_by sl.lengthSL\n```\n\n```tactics\nend SymList\n```\n\n```tactics\n/- # Exercicio 3.7 -/\n\ndef inits {α : Type} : List α → List (List α) :=\n (List.map List.reverse ∘ (Chapter1.scanl (flip List.cons) []))\n```\n\n```tactics\n/- # Exercicio 3.8  -/\n\ndef measure (ts : List (Tree a)) : Nat :=\n  ts.foldr (λ t acc => size t + acc) 0\n where\n  size : Tree a → Nat\n  | Tree.leaf _       => 1\n  | Tree.node _ t1 t2 => 1 + size t1 + size t2\n\ndef fromTs : List (Tree a) → List a\n| [] => []\n| (Tree.leaf x) :: ts =>\n  have : measure ts < measure (Tree.leaf x :: ts) := by\n   simp [measure,measure.size]\n  x :: fromTs ts\n| (Tree.node n t1 t2) :: ts =>\n  have : measure (t1 :: t2 :: ts) < measure (Tree.node n t1 t2 :: ts) := by\n   simp [measure, measure.size]\n   rw [Nat.add_assoc]; simp\n  fromTs (t1 :: t2 :: ts)\ntermination_by x1 => measure x1\n```\n\n```tactics\n-- 3.10\n\ndef toRA {a : Type} : List a → RAList a :=\n  List.foldr consRA nilRA\n```\n\nNow, we need to prove the theorem.",
