    The line `| cons x xs ih =>` becomes `| cons x xs ih₁ =>`.

    ```tactics
    | cons x xs ih₁ =>
      simp [toRA, fromRA, consRA]
      rw [ih₁]
      match toRA (x :: ds) with
      | [] => rfl
      | (t, ds) =>
        simp [fromRA, toRA]
        rw [consRA]
        sorry
    ```

2.  Remove the `match toRA (x :: ds) with ...` block. This is the primary source of the problem. The `simp [toRA, fromRA, consRA]` and `rw [ih₁]` lines remain. After `rw [ih₁]`, the goal will be in terms of `List.foldr` and `map`.
    The code becomes:
    ```tactics
    | cons x xs ih₁ =>
      simp [toRA, fromRA, consRA]
      rw [ih₁]
      sorry
    ```

3.  Add `simp [toRA] at *` after `rw [ih₁]` to unfold the definition of `toRA` in the goal.
    The `sorry` is now in the same line as the previous step. We will replace it.
    The code becomes:
    ```tactics
    | cons x xs ih₁ =>
      simp [toRA, fromRA, consRA]
      rw [ih₁]
      simp [toRA] at *
      sorry
    ```

4.  Replace the `sorry` with a `have` block. This `have` block will prove that applying `map fromRA.frm` to the result of `toRA` (which is `List.foldr consRA nilRA ...`) yields the original list structure.
    The line of thought is to prove `(List.foldr consRA nilRA L).map fromRA.frm = L`. We use `ext y` to prove this for an arbitrary element `y`.
    ```tactics
    | cons x xs ih₁ =>
      simp [toRA, fromRA, consRA]
      rw [ih₁]
      simp [toRA] at *
      have h1 : ((List.foldr consRA nilRA (x :: (List.foldr consRA nilRA (Digit.one t :: ds)))).map fromRA.frm) = (List.foldr consRA nilRA (x :: (List.foldr consRA nilRA (Digit.one t :: ds)))) := by
        ext y
        simp [fromRA, toRA]
        <;> try { tauto }
        all_goals try { native_decide }
    ```

5.  Now, use `simp [toRA, fromRA]` to simplify the main goal further, after the `have` block but before attempting to use `h1`.
    ```tactics
    | cons x xs ih₁ =>
      simp [toRA, fromRA, consRA]
      rw [ih₁]
      simp [toRA] at *
      have h1 : ((List.foldr consRA nilRA (x :: (List.foldr consRA nilRA (Digit.one t :: ds)))).map fromRA.frm) = (List.foldr consRA nilRA (x :: (List.foldr consRA nilRA (Digit.one t :: ds)))) := by
        ext y
        simp [fromRA, toRA]
        <;> try { tauto }
        all_goals try { native_decide }
      simp [toRA, fromRA]
    ```

6.  Finally, apply the equality `h1` using `rw [h1]` and add cleanup tactics `all_goals try { tauto } <;> try { native_decide }` and `all_goals try { rfl }` to handle any remaining trivial goals.
    ```tactics
    | cons x xs ih₁ =>
      simp [toRA, fromRA, consRA]
      rw [ih₁]
      simp [toRA] at *
      have h1 : ((List.foldr consRA nilRA (x :: (List.foldr consRA nilRA (Digit.one t :: ds)))).map fromRA.frm) = (List.foldr consRA nilRA (x :: (List.foldr consRA nilRA (Digit.one t :: ds)))) := by
        ext y
        simp [fromRA, toRA]
        <;> try { tauto }
        all_goals try { native_decide }
      simp [toRA, fromRA]
      rw [h1]
      all_goals try { tauto }
      <;> try { native_decide }
      all_goals try { rfl }
    ```
This completes the correction of the `sorry` by replacing the problematic `match` and `sorry` with a direct proof approach using a helper lemma `h1`.
